                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Cambon</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-01-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 22, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 441.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Referring again to Mr. de Margerie’s note
                    of the 22d ultimo, I have now the honor to inform you that the governor of
                    Oregon wrote on the 13th instant that he had again urged upon the local
                    authorities at Portland that they exercise diligence in observing the provisions
                    of the Franco-American consular convention of February 23, 1853, in order that
                    the French consular officers might have no further cause for complaint.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
